    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ibuprofen's non-selective binding to COX-1 and COX-2 is due to its relatively small size and similar shape to arachidonic acid, the natural substrate of COX enzymes. Arachidonic acid is a long-chain fatty acid that binds to the active site of COX enzymes, where it is converted to prostaglandins. Ibuprofen mimics the shape and size of arachidonic acid, allowing it to fit into the active site of COX enzymes. However, the COX enzymes have two slightly different active sites, one for COX-1 and one for COX-2. The difference between the two active sites is relatively small, and the shape and size of Ibuprofen are similar enough to both that it can bind to either one. This is why Ibuprofen is non-selective and can inhibit both COX-1 and COX-2. The small difference in the active sites doesn't allow Ibuprofen to preferentially bind to one over the other, leading to its non-selective inhibition of both COX enzymes. So, while Ibuprofen is effective in reducing inflammation and pain, its non-selective binding to COX enzymes can also lead to side effects such as stomach ulcers and increased",
      "source": "target",
